  "What does 'area between curves' mean?": "",
  "The integral of the absolute difference |f(x) - g(x)| over an interval, giving the total region enclosed between two curves": "",
  "The average of two areas based on the conventional understanding of how area processes interact in practice": "",
  "The product of two areas when the interaction between area and curves factors is taken into full account": "",
  "The area under the first curve minus the area under the second": "",
  "The area between curves f(x) and g(x) from a to b is integral of |f(x) - g(x)| dx. When f >= g on the entire interval, this simplifies to integral of (f(x) - g(x)) dx.": "",
  "What does 'upper curve minus lower curve' mean?": "",
  "Always subtract f from g, which is consistent with how curve mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "The order doesn't matter, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "Subtract the curve with the higher equation number, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "When computing area, subtract the lower (smaller y-value) function from the upper (larger y-value) function to keep the integrand positive": "",
  "To get a positive area, always write (top function) - (bottom function) as the integrand. If the curves switch positions, you need to split the integral at the crossing points.": "",
  "What is an 'intersection point' in the context of area between curves?": "",
  "A point where f(x) = g(x), which determines the limits of integration for the enclosed area": "",
  "The midpoint of the integration interval": "",
  "The highest point on either curve": "",
  "Where both curves cross the x-axis": "",
  "Intersection points are where the two curves meet: f(x) = g(x). These points define the boundaries of the enclosed region and serve as the limits of integration.": "",
  "What does 'integrating with respect to y' mean for area between curves?": "",
