  "Rotating the graph 90 degrees because conventional analysis of curves suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "Using y as the constant, since the relevant curves factors typically produce this outcome in practice": "",
  "Expressing both curves as functions of y (x = f(y) and x = g(y)) and integrating the horizontal distance between them along the y-axis": "",
  "When curves are better described as functions of y, integrate with respect to y: Area = integral from c to d of (right curve - left curve) dy. This avoids splitting the integral when curves don't pass the vertical line test.": "",
  "What does 'enclosed region' mean?": "",
  "The area under the first curve only": "",
  "An infinite region between the curves": "",
  "The bounded area completely surrounded by the given curves": "",
  "Any area near the curves": "",
  "An enclosed region is a finite area bounded on all sides by the given curves. The area between y = x^2 and y = x, for example, has an enclosed region between their intersection points x = 0 and x = 1.": "",
  "What is 'right curve minus left curve' when integrating with respect to y?": "",
  "The vertical distance between curves": "",
  "The curve to the right on the page minus the one to the left": "",
  "It doesn't matter which order": "",
  "The horizontal distance between curves: (rightmost x-value) - (leftmost x-value) at each y-level": "",
  "When integrating with respect to y, the integrand is (x_right - x_left) where x_right is the curve farther to the right at each y-value. This gives the width of horizontal slices through the region.": "",
  "What does 'splitting the integral' mean when finding area between curves?": "",
  "Using partial fractions, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "Integrating each curve separately under most circumstances involving curves": "",
  "Dividing the area in half, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "Breaking the integral into separate parts at points where the curves switch which one is on top": "",
  "When the upper and lower curves switch (one curve is on top for part of the interval and the other is on top for the rest), you must split the integral at the crossing point and ensure (top - bottom) is positive in each piece.": "",
  "What is a 'representative rectangle' for area between curves?": "",
  "A rectangle representing the total area": "",
  "A thin rectangle with width dx (or dy) and height equal to the distance between curves, used to set up the integral": "",
  "A rectangle drawn on graph paper": "",
  "The largest rectangle that fits between the curves": "",
  "A representative rectangle is a thin strip (vertical with width dx or horizontal with width dy) whose height or length equals the distance between the curves. Summing all such rectangles (via integration) gives the total area.": "",
  "What is a 'vertical slice' method for area?": "",
  "Using the y-axis as the axis of integration": "",
  "Only works for vertical curves": "",
  "Cutting the region with vertical lines into equal pieces": "",
  "Using thin vertical rectangles of width dx with height (top - bottom), integrating from left to right with respect to x": "",
  "The vertical slice method uses thin rectangles of width dx at each x. The height of each rectangle is f(x) - g(x) (top minus bottom). Area = integral from a to b of [f(x) - g(x)] dx.": "",
  "What is a 'horizontal slice' method for area?": "",
